      section.voice-and-tone#use-the-active    
        h4.purple-border Use the active voice
        .active-voice
          .active-left
            h4 Active voice: what a person or thing does.
            p Harry (subject) ate (verb) six shrimp (object) at dinner. 
            p The critic (subject) wrote (verb) a scathing review (object).
            p Matt (subject) leads (verb) the business team (object).
            p Dave (subject) reprogrammed (verb) the animatronic Chuck E. Cheese owl (object). 
          .passive-right
            h4 Passive voice: what is done to someone or something.
            p At dinner, six shrimp (object) were eaten (verb) by Harry (subject). 
            p A scathing review (object) was written (verb) by the critic (subject). 
            p The business team (object) is led (verb) by Matt (subject). 
            p The animatronic Chuck E. Cheese owl (object) was reprogrammed (verb) by Dave (subject).
        
        
        
      section.voice-and-tone#write-strong
        h4.purple-border Write strong ledes
        p Hit readers hard or lose them forever. If your lede (alternatively: lead) isn’t strong, the rest barely matters. 
        h5 To find your lede, ask yourself: 
        ul
          li What are the stakes?
          li How can I defy expectation? 
          li What makes this abstract idea concrete?
          li What do I want the reader to imagine?
        br
        p If you can’t find a strong lede, come back to the task later. Still nothing? Maybe it’s a sign that the article you want to write isn’t one people want to read. Change something drastically (theme, structure, scope, etc.) and try again, or shelve.
        p Writing about data and related subjects can be tough. It’s abstract, and hardly the most vivid way to represent the thrumming, vivid world we inhabit. Don’t let those cells imprison your prose! 
